post_text:
Friday Night Football vs. Williamsburg - AT Williamsburg
Important information for fans & spectators

Williamsburg vs Benton Community
September 4, 2020

Game Management Information
COVID-19 - Masks are required for all spectators at ALL events. If you need a short break from wearing your mask, please find an area away from all other spectators/competitors.

Concession stands will remain closed. Spectators may bring school-appropriate beverages into all games/meets. Food trucks may be available at some events. All food at indoor events should be consumed outside.

Ticket Info - Adults $5.00 & Students $5.00.

Fans - can park on the west grass area across West Street or in the main parking lot southeast of the high school. Benton Community fans will occupy the north bleachers. Ticket booths are located at the red areas on the map. We ask Benton Community fans to park in the main high school parking lot as a sidewalk goes around to the visitor's side on the east side.

Update for Bobcat Volleyball:

The volleyball on September 3rd was originally supposed to be played at Benton Community. The Derecho storm was brutal for us at Benton Community and our gym roof sustained damage. Our gym currently is deemed unplayable and water mitigation is taking place now.

Vinton-Shellsburg has graciously agreed to host this contest. Please adjust your calendar and travel to Vinton-Shellsburg to support our Bobcats on Sept. 3!

The schedule is as follows:

5:00 pm - JV Volleyball
5:00 pm - Freshman Volleyball
6:00 pm - Sophomore Volleyball
7:30 pm - Varsity Volleyball

Thank you!
Mr. Pfiffner, AD

Quick update:
High School/Middle School building undergoing water mitigation now. Roof damage to auditorium. Damage to gym roof area. Clean up continues. Athletic complex with a number of damages. Press box blown over onto center bleachers. Stadium light pole blown over.

I am discussing start of the school year and possible delayed start. Stat tuned!

post_text:
Benton Bobcats- please stay safe. We have a lot of trees and highline wires down across our county. We are thinking about and praying for all of our families and the damage to homes and farms from the derecho storm that hit Monday. As far as we know, everyone is safe. Cell service Monday and yesterday was nonexistent. Power still out. Our school buildings sustained some roof and water damage and we are working with our adjuster, roofing company, and cleaning/restoration. I will provide more updates as information becomes available.
Thank you to all of our community workers and volunteers as they begin the cleanup.

post_text:
Thank you to the Benton Community School District Food Service & Nutrition Department!

A brief summary of our Food For Kids program:

The BC Food for Kids program began March 23rd with the unexpected school closure and concluded on June 30th.

* Served meals from 7 sites throughout our district: meals were prepared by 9 employees and sites staffed by community volunteers

* Provided breakfast and lunches for 70 days, spanning 15 weeks.

* Prepared 30,908 breakfast and 30,908 lunches (60,816 total)

The Food for Kids program successfully served over 200 families in our district

post_text:
Food For Kids - June meals

Benton Community District notification for families who would like to participate in the Food For Kids program during JUNE.
If this does not apply to you, please disregard.

There is a NEW Sign-up for June meals: http://tinyurl.com/BCJuneMeals
Please sign-up to continue the Food For Kids Program through June.

Please note the following changes for the Food For Kids program during June:

Distribution sites will remain in the following towns at their current locations:
Atkins, Blairstown, Keystone, Newhall, Norway and Van Horne.

Meals will be available to be picked up on MONDAYS & THURSDAYS only.

On Mondays, you will receive meals for 3 days. On Thursday, you will receive meals for 2 days.

Lunches will be available from 11:00 a.m. to 12 Noon on Monday and Thursday.

Again, Please sign-up if you would like to continue receiving meals in June:

http://tinyurl.com/BCJuneMeals

post_text:
Congratulations to Coach Thomae on receiving the Golden Plaque Award from the IGHSAU. It is one of the highest honors given to a coach. Coach Thomae has been a tremendous leader for our track and cross country teams. Marty is also an outstanding educator. He continues to substitute teach, drives the bus whenever needed, and runs the weight room and speed training every afternoon. On top of all of that, Coach Thomae is a great role model, friend to everyone, and gets to the heart of what it means to be a BOBCAT.

Thanks for all you do, Coach Thomae! Congratulations!

2020 - 2021 D A N C E ⚡️ T E A M Virtual Tryouts, YAY!

Some important dates are listed below
To be added to the Dance Team Tryout Google Drive, you must complete the Google Form:

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfLB0NytqTfgnU70GTJb4yxTZsV0iNuhj6WhKyxd91iG6lyMQ/viewform

It is due by 6:00 P.M. on May 15th.

On May 19th, at 7 P.M. we will have a parent meeting via Zoom, dancers should be present as well!

If this does not work for you, or you do not have internet access, please let Coach Botkin know ASAP! 🤗

Further information about the tryout process will be discussed at the Zoom meeting.

Please share this information with your favorite dancer! If you have any questions regarding Dance Team, please contact Coach Botkin at kbotkin@benton.k12.ia.us.

Some important dates are listed below
To be added to the Dance Team Tryout Google Drive, you must complete the Google Form:

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfLB0NytqTfgnU70GTJb4yxTZsV0iNuhj6WhKyxd91iG6lyMQ/viewform

It is due by 6:00 P.M. on May 15th.

On May 19th, at 7 P.M. we will have a parent meeting via Zoom, dancers should be present as well!

If this does not work for you, or you do not have internet access, please let Coach Botkin know ASAP! 🤗

Further information about the tryout process will be discussed at the Zoom meeting.

Please share this information with your favorite dancer! If you have any questions regarding Dance Team, please contact Coach Botkin at kbotkin@benton.k12.ia.us.

post_text:
The Marching Bobcats are excited to announce their 2020 show, "Beyond the Stars". Our Color Guard is an integral part of our band program and we would love to welcome new members for the coming season! The Benton Color Guard has won numerous Best in Class awards at field competitions in recent years and is the reigning Class 2 State Champion for Winter Guard. The group is made up of a mixture of band and non-band members. Experience in music or dance is a bonus, but not required. If you are interested in being a part of our 2020 Benton Color Guard, please complete the following Google Form by Friday, May 1st and send onto anyone else you think might be interested! For questions, please contact Mr. Tipping at ctipping@benton.k12.ia.us

https://forms.gle/oPP5RptfHrWYLTtc7 (Use this form)

post_text:
Happy Friday, Bobcats! Mr. Meyne is passing along some positivity this morning by sharing the story below. Stay safe and well!

“Kindra Neis, a Benton Community Junior, worked diligently on creating a Computer Aided Drafting (CAD) file of a USA flag. She researched the standard dimensions for all features of the flag and was extremely particular about all measurements. Once the design work was complete, Kindra used the Computer Numerical Control (CNC) Plasma Arc Cutter (PAC) to cut the 3/8” mild steel. After some grinding and durable painting, the project was ready to go on display. Kindra has been an active student in the Benton Industrial Technology and Engineering program, where she learned the skills and knowledge to operate the equipment to fabricate projects like this. Kindra currently plans to attend Iowa State University after graduating, where she will major in Mechanical Engineering.”

shared_text:
Benton Community FFA
March 24 at 12:17 PM ·

Happy National Ag Day! 🎉

This week we typically hold our Drive Your Tractor to School Day. This allows our members to bring awareness of the agriculture industry as our whole student body and staff see the tractors all lined up in the front parking lot. As we honor this day, our members salute our agriculture industry by our modified Drive Your Tractor to School Day, making the best of our circumstances. 🚜 We cannot thank our food supply chain enough for the work they continue to put in so we have food on our tables, not to mention the thousands of products we use daily that contain byproducts from agriculture.

Thank You to ALL in the agriculture industry. YOU are appreciated! 💙

{Members who participated: Will Schmidt, Mya Meyer, Raynee LaGrange, Trinity LaGrange, Cameron Keiper, Zach Strasser, Abbie Kaestner, Dylan Bossler, Tyler Atkinson, Quintin Volesky, Justin Bierschenk, Alex Ludeking, and Jacob Ludeking}

March 23 at 4:51 PM ·

CHANGE IN PROCEDURE: Iowa DOT driver's service centers will be open by appointment for essential services ONLY from March 24 to May 1. Call your local service center to schedule an appointment. Find that contact information on https://iowadot.gov/mvd/Service-centers.

Examples of essential services that will be offered by appointment in our service centers are a customer who:
* has a commercial driver’s license or chauffeur’s license service need.
* may need services before May 1 related to a specific event such as starting a new job or to fulfill a work-related requirement, a financial loan or other financial business, school/education-related, to obtain benefits of any kind, or for a legal-related purpose.

post_text:
BC Students and Families,

The intent of this newsletter is to provide students and families with information on digital resources to access remotely to maintain academic skills during this COVID-19 school closure. The school closure situation is fluid. As a district, we will continue to provide information as it becomes available.

At this point, the plan is to provide an updated list of digital curricular resources each week school is closed. Again, this may change as information and direction become available at the federal and state levels.

We know and understand these digital resources can in no way replace or replicate the impact teachers have on students in a collaborative, in-person learning environment. If you have specific questions about the resources shared, please reach out to Anna Upah, Director of Curriculum and Instructional Services. (aupah@benton.k12.ia.us)

As always, our goal is to provide Bobcats with a Quality Education for a Lifetime of Learning. Through all of this, we will show that Benton Community truly is A Place to Belong.

https://www.smore.com/eychr

The district will consider the retrieval of student medications that may be currently located at the school buildings.
If you need access to your child’s medication, the buildings will be open from 4-6 PM TODAY, MARCH 16.
Medications will only be returned to the parent of the child who the medication is prescribed to.
More information about access to other student materials that may have been left in the buildings will be forthcoming.
Thank you,
Office of the Superintendent

Próximamente se proporcionará más información sobre el acceso a otros materiales estudiantiles que puedan haber quedado en los edificios.

shared_text:
Benton Community FFA
March 14 at 3:50 PM ·

Congratulations to the Conduct of Meetings team for their 2nd place Gold finish today at the NE "Virtual" District Convention! The team of Easton Patterson, Ryan Grace, Keaten Volesky, Kait Ballard, Zach Grace, Emma Von Ahsen, and Addison Phillips will compete at State Leadership Conference next month!

Awesome job to our Ag Issues and Perceptions team of Jacob Ludeking, Kohle Ballard, Alex Ludeking, Abbie Kaestner, Tyler Atkinson & Dylan Bossler receiving a Silver rating and alternate to state!

Great work to our Parliamentary Procedure team of Raynee LaGrange, Trinity LaGrange, Mya Meyer, Emily Ingalls and Garret Coffland receiving a Silver rating and are excited to practice throughout the year to do parli again next year!

A huge shout out to our District Advisor and District and State Officers for running our districts virtually this year. I am sure it was not easy and super stressful but all in all, everything went extremely well considering the circumstances.

Alumni Spotlight:
Debra (Bell) Miner
Graduated Benton - 1986
After Benton - Northwest Missouri State University, BS Elementary Education/Early Childhood
Marycrest University, MA in Education
Residence - Van Horne, IA

Debra started her 27 year teaching career in Kansas City, Missouri before returning to Iowa. Debra is currently teaching 5th grade at Norway Intermediate. She and her husband Matt (BC graduate 1988) have 3 daughters who have graduated or attend Benton Community. When not working, you may find Debra in the bleachers at many BC activities supporting her students and children at her alma mater.

This is a message from the Benton Community School District.
The Benton Community School District will make up one of our missed school days on Wednesday, March 18.
To repeat, we will hold school on Wednesday, March 18th.

post_text:
Students at Benton Community MS/HS have been celebrating National FFA Week. As the week comes to a close, we want to take an opportunity to recognize our FFA Advisor and Ag Teacher, Krystal Wright. Below are a few comments from students about the positive impact she has had on them. Thank you, Mrs. Wright!

“Mrs. Wright has impacted me a lot through FFA. She has pushed me to go out of my comfort zone many times, which I am grateful for. I have learned many social and leadership skills through her positivity in believing in me and what I can do.”

"Mrs. Wright has been my Ag teacher now for 4 years. Each year, our bond has only gotten stronger and she is one of the biggest supporters I have! If I need to talk about FFA related things or not, I know she is always there for me. They say the impact of a good teacher will never be forgotten. As a senior, I can’t describe how much I will miss having her as a teacher. I will never forget the impact she made on my high school years."

post_text:
Alumni Spotlight:
Emily (Thompson) Miltenberger
Graduated Benton - 2007
After Benton - Central College (2011)—Political science, Mercy College of Health Sciences (2014)—Nursing
Residence - Des Moines, IA

Emily went straight to Central College from BCHS with intentions to go pre-med and then on to medical school. After one year, it was clear this was not the journey she was supposed to take, so she switched to Political Science with the intent to go to law school after graduation (participation in a mock trial is what made Emily decide pre-law was the right track). Emily graduated with a Bachelor’s Degree in 2011 and took a gap year to do AmeriCorps VISTA. During this year, she met a nurse who gently pushed Emily to look into nursing. She once again changed her track and applied for nursing school. She attended Mercy College of Health Sciences and graduated with an associate's degree in 2014 and has worked as a nurse ever since!

Alumni Spotlight:
Suzanne (Holst) Revers
Graduated Benton - 1981
After Benton - Kirkwood Community College
Residence - Cedar Rapids, IA

Suzanne went to Kirkwood Community College and worked as an Accountant for various companies until she became a business owner in 1995. She owned and operated Music Go Round, a national franchise, buying and selling used and new musical instruments for over 17 years in Cedar Rapids and Des Moines, Iowa. For the past eight years she’s been following her passion for serving individuals with disabilities and is a Mentor providing one-on-one coaching through The Mentor Network. Suzanne lives in Cedar Rapids and is mom to her adult son Andy (who was born with Down Syndrome,) teenage son, Dawson, and daughter Janaha who is married and has two little girls.

post_text:
Alumni Spotlight:
Austin Cassell
Graduated Benton - 2012
After Benton - Associates of Applied Science
Residence - Marion, IA

After graduating from Benton Community, Austin attended Luther college. Austin was fortunate to become the starting punter for the Norse football team and was awarded Special Teams Player of the Year. Following his freshman year, Austin transferred to Kirkwood Community College to obtain his Associates Degree. Austin was then accepted into the Mercy/St. Luke’s School of Radiology. Upon graduating, Austin received an award for clinical excellence throughout the program. Austin recently returned from living in Portland, Oregon with his wife Ashley and dog Mia. He would like to encourage all to get out of your comfort zone and travel when you get the opportunity. Austin is currently returning to school in hopes to become a Registered Radiologic Assistant.

Due to the anticipated inclement weather, we are dismissing today at 1:00 p.m.

Thank you,
The Office of the Superintendent and Activities Director

Gracias,
La Oficina del Superintendente y Director de Actividades

post_text:
10th, 11th, and 12th graders and Families,
There are group job shadow opportunities for the spring semester. See the attachment for a list of the second round group job shadows and their descriptions. The job shadow page of our www.workplace-learning.org portal is open today and closes on January 21st at 3pm.

Space is limited so please apply early. It is possible that students will not receive a placement even if their approvals are in by our deadline if the shadows they are interested in fill up quickly. Students will need all approvals in by 3pm on January 21st to be considered.

Students that completed a fall job shadow (or signed up for one but hasn’t been placed yet) can still participate in a spring group job shadow as well.

If you have any questions please contact Mrs. Nesbitt.

post_text:
The Benton Robotics teams competed this past weekend. Both teams had a great competition. Benton Robotics Team 5153 - Error 404 won the second place Innovate Award. They had a great season.

Benton Robotics team 3788 - Catastrophic Failure won the third place Collins Aerospace Design Award, was in the finalist alliance, and advanced to the Super Qualifiers in Johnston on Feb 1st.

FTC Teams advance from League Championships to Super Qualifiers, from Super Qualifiers to State, from State to World's.
